
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `avahi-browse-domains` baraye peyda kardan domain-haye morede estefade az tarigh Avahi (yek system baraye service discovery) be kar miravad. In dastoor be shoma komak mikonad domain-haye mahalli ke service-ha dar aanha mojood hastand ra peyda konid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `avahi-browse-domains -t` --> ⏱️ Tanha domain-ha ra yek bar namayesh dade va khateme bede. Be jaye monitor kardan taghirat.
    🔹 `avahi-browse-domains -v` --> 🗣️ Ezafe kardan etela'at bishtar be khorooji, mesle flag-ha.
    🔹 `avahi-browse-domains --all` --> 🌐 Namayesh hameye domain-ha, hata domain-haye static.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ avahi-browse-domains

    🔹 List kardan domain-haye mahalli mojood.

    $ avahi-browse-domains -t

    🔹 List kardan domain-ha, va baad az an khorooj.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ avahi-browse-domains

    Output mesal:
    + wlan0 IPv4 local                                              domains
    + wlan0 IPv6 local                                              domains
    = wlan0 IPv4 local                                              local
    = wlan0 IPv6 local                                              local

    🔹 In mesal neshon midahad ke system domain "local" ra peyda karde ast, ham az tarigh IPv4 va ham IPv6, rooye interface wlan0.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `avahi-browse-domains` command is used to discover domains available through Avahi, which is a system for service discovery. This command helps you find local domains where services are available.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `avahi-browse-domains -t` --> ⏱️ Only list the domains once and then exit, instead of monitoring for changes.
    🔹 `avahi-browse-domains -v` --> 🗣️ Add more verbosity to the output, such as flags.
    🔹 `avahi-browse-domains --all` --> 🌐 Show all domains, including static ones.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ avahi-browse-domains

    🔹 List the available local domains.

    $ avahi-browse-domains -t

    🔹 List the domains once, and then exit.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ avahi-browse-domains

    Example output:
    + wlan0 IPv4 local                                              domains
    + wlan0 IPv6 local                                              domains
    = wlan0 IPv4 local                                              local
    = wlan0 IPv6 local                                              local

    🔹 This example shows that the system discovered the "local" domain, both via IPv4 and IPv6, on the wlan0 interface.
